result.execSummary:
The defendant Shaquille M Gilbert was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Carry Concealed Weapon, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.23(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Shaquille M Gilbert in court with attorney Brian Christopher Hagner.  Sarah McNutt appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk cmt.
Case scheduled for Jury Trial. Parties ready to proceed with plea/sentencing.
As to Count 1:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the Defendant guilty and enters judgment of conviction into the record forthwith. 

As to Count 2:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on State's motion, Court orders Count 2 DISMISSED but read-in as to sentencing.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by parties.  
As to Count 1:  Court ordered SENTENCE WITHHELD, with credit for 1 day time served, and placed the defendant on probation for 12 months with the following conditions:
 - Defendant is to serve 90 days in the House of Correction, condition time, Court stays 75 days.  Defendant to serve 15 days with Huber Privileges for work, Court stays the report date to 8-03-2015 at 4pm. Court does not object to electronic monitoring.
 - No use or possession of any dangerous weapons or firearms. 
 - Turn over CCW permit.
 - No new violations that rise to the level of probable cause.
 - Make diligent efforts to obtain GED/HSED. 
 - 200 hours of community service.
 - Pay all costs, fees and surcharges during term of probation or civil judgment.

  Court will consider motion for expungement  if defendant successfully completes terms of probation and has no further violations of the law.
